					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div role=3D"note" c=
lass=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">For other uses, see <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecast_(disambiguation)" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t mw-disambig" title=3D"Forecast (disambiguation)">Forecast</a>.</div>
<div class=3D"shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=
=3D"display:none">Making predictions based on available data</div>
<p><b>Forecasting</b> is the process of making predictions based on <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Past" title=3D"Past">past</a> and present=
 data. Later these can be compared with what actually happens. For example,=
 a company might <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Estimation" title=
=3D"Estimation">estimate</a> their revenue in the next year, then compare i=
t against the actual results creating a variance actual analysis. <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prediction" title=3D"Prediction">Predicti=
on</a> is a similar but more general term. Forecasting might refer to speci=
fic formal statistical methods employing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Time_series" title=3D"Time series">time series</a>, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross-sectional_data" title=3D"Cross-sectional dat=
a">cross-sectional</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Longitud=
inal_study" title=3D"Longitudinal study">longitudinal</a> data, or alternat=
ively to less formal judgmental methods or the process of prediction and as=
sessment of its accuracy. Usage can vary between areas of application: for =
example, in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrology" title=3D"Hy=
drology">hydrology</a> the terms "forecast" and "forecasting" are sometimes=
 reserved for estimates of values at certain specific <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Future" title=3D"Future">future</a> times, while the te=
rm "prediction" is used for more general estimates, such as the number of t=
imes floods will occur over a long period.
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><br>
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Risk" title=3D"Risk">Risk</a> and =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uncertainty" title=3D"Uncertainty"=
>uncertainty</a> are central to forecasting and prediction; it is generally=
 considered a good practice to indicate the degree of uncertainty attaching=
 to forecasts. In any case, the data must be up to date in order for the fo=
recast to be as accurate as possible. In some cases the data used to predic=
t the variable of interest is itself forecast.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_no=
te-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> A forecast is not to be confused with a Budget; budgets ar=
e more specific, fixed-term financial plans used for resource allocation an=
d control, while forecasts provide estimates of future financial performanc=
e, allowing for flexibility and adaptability to changing circumstances.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  Both tools are valuable in financ=
ial planning and decision-making, but they serve different functions.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DForecasting&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Applications"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<p>Forecasting has applications in a wide range of fields where estimates o=
f future conditions are useful. Depending on the field, accuracy varies sig=
nificantly. If the factors that relate to what is being forecast are known =
and well understood and there is a significant amount of data that can be u=
sed, it is likely the final value will be close to the forecast. If this is=
 not the case or if the actual outcome is affected by the forecasts, the re=
liability of the forecasts can be significantly lower.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-h=
ttps://www.otexts.org/fpp/1/1_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-https://www.otexts.org/fpp/1/1-4=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>=20
</p><p>Climate change and increasing energy prices have led to the use of <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egain_Forecasting" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Egain Forecasting">Egain Forecasting</a> for buildings. This=
 attempts to reduce the energy needed to heat the building, thus reducing t=
he emission of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greenhouse_gas" tit=
le=3D"Greenhouse gas">greenhouse gases</a>. Forecasting is used in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Customer_demand_planning" title=3D"Custom=
er demand planning">customer demand planning</a> in everyday business for m=
anufacturing and distribution companies.
</p><p>While the veracity of predictions for actual stock returns are dispu=
ted through reference to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Effic=
ient-market_hypothesis" title=3D"Efficient-market hypothesis">efficient-mar=
ket hypothesis</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_forec=
asting" title=3D"Economic forecasting">forecasting of broad economic trends=
</a> is common. Such analysis is provided by both non-profit groups as well=
 as by for-profit private institutions.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Templat=
e Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation nee=
ded"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (Janua=
ry 2019)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>Forecasting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exchange_rate" =
title=3D"Exchange rate">foreign exchange</a> movements is typically achieve=
d through a combination of historical and current data (summarized in chart=
s) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_analysis" title=
=3D"Fundamental analysis">fundamental analysis</a>. An essential difference=
 between chart analysis and fundamental economic analysis is that chartists=
 study only the price action of a market, whereas fundamentalists attempt t=
o look to the reasons behind the action.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-5"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> Financial institutions assimilate the evidence provided by their =
fundamental and chartist researchers into one note to provide a final proje=
ction on the currency in question.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-InstutionalResearch_6=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecastin=
g#cite_note-InstutionalResearch-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Forecasting has also been used to predict the development of conflic=
t situations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Forecasters perfo=
rm research that uses empirical results to gauge the effectiveness of certa=
in forecasting models.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-faq_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-faq-8"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> However research has shown that there is little difference between the ac=
curacy of the forecasts of experts knowledgeable in the conflict situation =
and those by individuals who knew much less.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-=
9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> Similarly, experts in some studies argue that role thinking =
=E2=80=94 standing in other people's shoes to forecast their decisions =E2=
=80=94 does not contribute to the accuracy of the forecast.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foreca=
sting#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>An important, albeit often ignored aspect of forecasting, is the rel=
ationship it holds with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planning" =
title=3D"Planning">planning</a>. Forecasting can be described as predicting=
 what the future <i>will</i> look like, whereas planning predicts what the =
future <i>should</i> look like.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-faq_8-1" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-faq-8">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> There is no single right forecasting method to use. Selection of=
 a method should be based on your objectives and your conditions (data etc.=
).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A good way to find a meth=
od is by visiting a selection tree. An example of a selection tree can be f=
ound here.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Forecasting has application in many situations:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supply_chain_management" t=
itle=3D"Supply chain management">Supply chain management</a> and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Customer_demand_planning" title=3D"Customer =
demand planning">customer demand planning</a> =E2=80=94 Forecasting can be =
used in supply chain management to ensure that the right product is at the =
right place at the right time. Accurate forecasting will help retailers red=
uce excess inventory and thus increase <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Profit_margin" title=3D"Profit margin">profit margin</a>. Accurate for=
ecasting will also help them meet consumer demand. The discipline of demand=
 planning, also sometimes referred to as supply chain forecasting, embraces=
 both statistical forecasting and a consensus process. Studies have shown t=
hat extrapolations are the least accurate, while company earnings forecasts=
 are the most reliable.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"marg=
in-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" title=3D"Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span ti=
tle=3D"The text near this tag may need clarification or removal of jargon. =
(December 2013)">clarification needed</span></a></i>]</sup><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foreca=
sting#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_forecasting" title=3D=
"Economic forecasting">Economic forecasting</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earthquake_prediction" title=
=3D"Earthquake prediction">Earthquake prediction</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egain_forecasting" title=3D"Eg=
ain forecasting">Egain forecasting</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Energy_forecasting" title=3D"E=
nergy forecasting">Energy forecasting</a> for renewable power integration</=
li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finance" title=3D"Finance">Fin=
ance</a> against risk of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Default_(=
finance)" title=3D"Default (finance)">default</a> via <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Credit_rating" title=3D"Credit rating">credit ratings</=
a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Credit_score" title=3D"Cred=
it score">credit scores</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Land_use_forecasting" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Land use forecasting">Land use forecasting</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PECOTA" title=3D"PECOTA">Playe=
r and team performance in sports</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Political_forecasting" title=
=3D"Political forecasting">Political forecasting</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Product_forecasting" title=3D"=
Product forecasting">Product forecasting</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sales_forecasting" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Sales forecasting">Sales forecasting</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technology_forecasting" title=
=3D"Technology forecasting">Technology forecasting</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Telecommunications_forecasting=
" title=3D"Telecommunications forecasting">Telecommunications forecasting</=
a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transport_planning" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Transport planning">Transport planning</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transportation_forecasting" title=3D"Tran=
sportation forecasting">forecasting</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weather_forecasting" title=3D"=
Weather forecasting">Weather forecasting</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Flood_forecasting" title=3D"Flood forecasting">flood forecastin=
g</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meteorology" title=3D"Me=
teorology">meteorology</a></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Forecasting_as_training,_be=
tting_and_futarchy"><span id=3D"Forecasting_as_training.2C_betting_and_futa=
rchy"></span>Forecasting as training, betting and futarchy</h2><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DForecasting&amp;action=3De=
dit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Forecasting as training, bettin=
g and futarchy"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>In several cases, the forecast is either more or less than a prediction =
of the future.
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_E._Tetlock" title=
=3D"Philip E. Tetlock">Philip E. Tetlock</a>'s <i><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Superforecasting:_The_Art_and_Science_of_Prediction" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Superforecasting: The Art and Science of Predicti=
on">Superforecasting: The Art and Science of Prediction</a></i>, he discuss=
es forecasting as a method of improving the ability to make decisions. A pe=
rson can become better calibrated<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Temp=
late-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><=
span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (January 202=
2)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> =E2=80=94 <i>i.e.</i> having thin=
gs they give 10% credence to happening 10% of the time. Or they can forecas=
t things more confidently<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fac=
t" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span tit=
le=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (January 2022)">cita=
tion needed</span></a></i>]</sup> =E2=80=94 coming to the same conclusion b=
ut earlier. Some have claimed that forecasting is a transferable skill with=
 benefits to other areas of discussion and decision making.<sup class=3D"no=
print Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wi=
kipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reli=
able sources. (January 2022)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Betting" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Betting">Betting</a> on sports or politics is another form of =
forecasting. Rather than being used as advice, bettors are paid based on if=
 they predicted correctly. While decisions might be made based on these bet=
s (forecasts), the main motivation is generally financial.
</p><p>Finally, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Futarchy" title=3D=
"Futarchy">futarchy</a> is a form of government where forecasts of the impa=
ct of government action are used to decide which actions are taken. Rather =
than advice, in futarchy's strongest form, the action with the best forecas=
ted result is automatically taken.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Tem=
plate-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed">=
<span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (January 20=
22)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Forecast_improvements">Fore=
cast improvements</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DForecasting&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Forecast improvements"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Forecast improvement projects have been operated in a number of sectors:=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Hurricane_Center" ti=
tle=3D"National Hurricane Center">National Hurricane Center</a>'s Hurricane=
 Forecast Improvement Project (HFIP) and the Wind Forecast Improvement Proj=
ect sponsored by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/US_Department=
_of_Energy" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"US Department of Energy">US Depa=
rtment of Energy</a> are examples.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-14"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> In relation to supply chain management, the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/DuPont_analysis" title=3D"DuPont analysis">Du Pont model</=
a> has been used to show that an increase in forecast accuracy can generate=
 increases in sales and reductions in inventory, operating expenses and com=
mitment of working capital.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-15"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Groceries_Code_Adjudicator" t=
itle=3D"Groceries Code Adjudicator">Groceries Code Adjudicator</a> in the U=
nited Kingdom, which regulates supply chain management practices in the gro=
ceries retail industry, has observed that all the retailers who fall within=
 the scope of his regulation "are striving for continuous improvement in fo=
recasting practice and activity in relation to promotions".<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foreca=
sting#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Categories_of_forecasting_m=
ethods">Categories of forecasting methods</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DForecasting&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4=
" title=3D"Edit section: Categories of forecasting methods"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Qualitative_vs._quantitativ=
e_methods">Qualitative vs. quantitative methods</h3><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DForecasting&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;secti=
on=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Qualitative vs. quantitative methods"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Qualitative forecasting techniques are subjective, based on the opinion =
and judgment of consumers and experts; they are appropriate when past data =
are not available.
They are usually applied to intermediate- or long-range decisions. Examples=
 of qualitative forecasting methods are<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Templat=
e Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation nee=
ded"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (May 2=
012)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> informed opinion and judgment, =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delphi_method" title=3D"Delphi=
 method">Delphi method</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Market=
_research" title=3D"Market research">market research</a>, and historical li=
fe-cycle analogy.
</p><p>Quantitative forecasting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
thematical_model" title=3D"Mathematical model">models</a> are used to forec=
ast future data as a function of past data. They are appropriate to use whe=
n past numerical data is available and when it is reasonable to assume that=
 some of the patterns in the data are expected to continue into the future.
These methods are usually applied to short- or intermediate-range decisions=
. Examples of quantitative forecasting methods are<sup class=3D"noprint Inl=
ine-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:C=
itation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sour=
ces. (May 2012)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> last period demand, =
simple and weighted N-Period <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Movin=
g_average" title=3D"Moving average">moving averages</a>, simple <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_smoothing" title=3D"Exponential s=
moothing">exponential smoothing</a>, Poisson process model based forecastin=
g<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and multiplicative seasona=
l indexes. Previous research shows that different methods may lead to diffe=
rent level of forecasting accuracy. For example, <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Group_method_of_data_handling" title=3D"Group method of data=
 handling">GMDH</a> neural network was found to have  better forecasting pe=
rformance than the classical forecasting algorithms such as Single Exponent=
ial Smooth, Double Exponential Smooth, ARIMA and back-propagation neural ne=
twork.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Average_approach">Average a=
pproach</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFore=
casting&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Average a=
pproach"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>In this approach, the predictions of all future values are equal to the =
mean of the past data. This approach can be used with any sort of data wher=
e past data is available. In time series notation:
