<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Time_series_methods">Time s=
eries methods</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DForecasting&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: T=
ime series methods"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_series" title=3D"Time seri=
es">Time series</a> methods use historical data as the basis of estimating =
future outcomes. They are based on the assumption that past demand history =
is a good indicator of future demand.
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moving_average" title=3D"M=
oving average">Moving average</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weighted_moving_average" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Weighted moving average">Weighted moving average<=
/a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_smoothing" title=
=3D"Exponential smoothing">Exponential smoothing</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autoregressive%E2%80%93moving-=
average_model" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Autoregressive=E2=80=93moving=
-average model">Autoregressive moving average (ARMA)</a> (forecasts depend =
on past values of the variable being forecast and on past prediction errors=
)</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autoregressive_integrated_movi=
ng_average" title=3D"Autoregressive integrated moving average">Autoregressi=
ve integrated moving average (ARIMA)</a> (ARMA on the period-to-period chan=
ge in the forecast variable)</li></ul>
<dl><dd>e.g. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box%E2%80%93Jenkins" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Box=E2=80=93Jenkins">Box=E2=80=93Jenkins</a>=
</dd>
<dd>Seasonal ARIMA or SARIMA or ARIMARCH,</dd></dl>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extrapolation" title=3D"Ex=
trapolation">Extrapolation</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_prediction" title=3D"Li=
near prediction">Linear prediction</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trend_estimation" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Trend estimation">Trend estimation</a> (predicting the v=
ariable as a linear or polynomial function of time)</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Growth_curve_(statistics)" tit=
le=3D"Growth curve (statistics)">Growth curve (statistics)</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recurrent_neural_network" titl=
e=3D"Recurrent neural network">Recurrent neural network</a></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Relational_methods">Relatio=
nal methods</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Forecasting&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Rela=
tional methods"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>Some forecasting methods try to identify the underlying factors that mig=
ht influence the variable that is being forecast. For example, including in=
formation about climate patterns might improve the ability of a model to pr=
edict umbrella sales. Forecasting models often take account of regular seas=
onal variations. In addition to climate, such variations can also be due to=
 holidays and customs: for example, one might predict that sales of college=
 football apparel will be higher during the football season than during the=
 off season.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NahmiasOlsen2015_22-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-NahmiasOlsen=
2015-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Several informal methods used in causal forecasting do not rely sole=
ly on the output of mathematical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
lgorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithms</a>, but instead use the judgment =
of the forecaster. Some forecasts take account of past relationships betwee=
n variables: if one variable has, for example, been approximately linearly =
related to another for a long period of time, it may be appropriate to extr=
apolate such a relationship into the future, without necessarily understand=
ing the reasons for the relationship.
</p><p>Causal methods include:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regression_analysis" title=
=3D"Regression analysis">Regression analysis</a> includes a large group of =
methods for predicting future values of a variable using information about =
other variables. These methods include both <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Parametric_statistics" title=3D"Parametric statistics">parametric=
</a> (linear or non-linear) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/No=
nparametric_regression" title=3D"Nonparametric regression">non-parametric</=
a> techniques.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ARMAX" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"ARMAX">Autoregressive moving average with exogenous inputs (ARMAX)<=
/a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>Quantitative forecasting models are often judged against each other by c=
omparing their in-sample or out-of-sample <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Mean_square_error" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mean square error=
">mean square error</a>, although some researchers have advised against thi=
s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Different forecasting app=
roaches have different levels of accuracy. For example, it was found in one=
 context that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GMDH" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"GMDH">GMDH</a> has higher forecasting accuracy than tradit=
ional ARIMA.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Judgmental_methods">Judgmen=
tal methods</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Forecasting&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Judg=
mental methods"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>Judgmental forecasting methods incorporate intuitive judgement, opinions=
 and subjective <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability" title=
=3D"Probability">probability</a> estimates. Judgmental forecasting is used =
in cases where there is a lack of historical data or during completely new =
and unique market conditions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-26"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>Judgmental methods include:
</p>
<ul><li>Composite forecasts<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-F=
act" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span t=
itle=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (January 2019)">ci=
tation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></li>
<li>Cooke's method<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" styl=
e=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wiki=
pedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"T=
his claim needs references to reliable sources. (January 2019)">citation ne=
eded</span></a></i>]</sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delphi_method" title=3D"Delphi=
 method">Delphi method</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecast_by_analogy" title=3D"=
Forecast by analogy">Forecast by analogy</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scenario_planning" title=3D"Sc=
enario planning">Scenario building</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_survey" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Statistical survey">Statistical surveys</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technology_forecasting" title=
=3D"Technology forecasting">Technology forecasting</a></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Artificial_intelligence_met=
hods">Artificial intelligence methods</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DForecasting&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" t=
itle=3D"Edit section: Artificial intelligence methods"><span>edit</span></a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_neural_networks=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Artificial neural networks">Artificial neu=
ral networks</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_method_of_data_handling"=
 title=3D"Group method of data handling">Group method of data handling</a><=
/li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Support_vector_machine" title=
=3D"Support vector machine">Support vector machines</a></li></ul>
<p>Often these are done today by specialized programs loosely labeled
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_mining" title=3D"Data=
 mining">Data mining</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machine_learning" title=3D"Mac=
hine learning">Machine learning</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pattern_recognition" title=3D"=
Pattern recognition">Pattern recognition</a></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Geometric_extrapolation_wit=
h_error_prediction">Geometric extrapolation with error prediction</h3><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DForecasting&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Geometric extrapolation w=
ith error prediction"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Can be created with 3 points of a sequence and the "moment" or "index". =
This type of extrapolation has 100% accuracy in predictions in a big percen=
tage of known series database (OEIS).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-27"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other_methods">Other method=
s</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DForecastin=
g&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: Other methods"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Granger_causality" title=
=3D"Granger causality">Granger causality</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simulation" title=3D"Simulatio=
n">Simulation</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Demand_forecasting" title=3D"D=
emand forecasting">Demand forecasting</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probabilistic_forecasting" tit=
le=3D"Probabilistic forecasting">Probabilistic forecasting</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ensemble_forecasting" title=3D"Ensemble f=
orecasting">Ensemble forecasting</a></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Forecasting_accuracy">Forec=
asting accuracy</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DForecasting&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: =
Forecasting accuracy"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The forecast error (also known as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Errors_and_residuals" title=3D"Errors and residuals">residual</a>) is =
the difference between the actual value and the forecast value for the corr=
esponding period:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \ E_{t}=3DY_{t}-F_{t}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mtext>&nbsp;</mtext>
        <msub>
          <mi>E</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>t</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>Y</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>t</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>F</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>t</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \ E_{t}=3DY_{=
t}-F_{t}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/c9cd9a0cf23736318a41a86f87f3681ba70a9319" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:13.558ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \ =
E_{t}=3DY_{t}-F_{t}}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>where E is the forecast error at period t, Y is the actual value at peri=
od t, and F is the forecast for period t.
</p><p>A good forecasting method will yield residuals that are <b>uncorrela=
ted</b>. If there are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation"=
 title=3D"Correlation">correlations</a> between residual values, then there=
 is information left in the residuals which should be used in computing for=
ecasts. This can be accomplished by computing the expected value of a resid=
ual as a function of the known past residuals, and adjusting the forecast b=
y the amount by which this expected value differs from zero.
</p><p>A good forecasting method will also have <b>zero mean</b>. If the re=
siduals have a mean other than zero, then the forecasts are biased and can =
be improved by adjusting the forecasting technique by an additive constant =
that equals the mean of the unadjusted residuals.
</p><p>Measures of aggregate error:
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Scaled-dependent_errors">Sc=
aled-dependent errors</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DForecasting&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Scaled-dependent errors"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The forecast error, E, is on the same scale as the data, as such, these =
accuracy measures are scale-dependent and cannot be used to make comparison=
s between series on different scales.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean_absolute_error" title=
=3D"Mean absolute error">Mean absolute error</a> (MAE) or <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_absolute_deviation" title=3D"Average absolu=
te deviation">mean absolute deviation</a> (MAD): <span class=3D"mwe-math-el=
ement mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-ma=
th-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1=
