-align: -2.671ex; width:23.561ex; height:6.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \ =
SS=3D1-{\frac {MSE_{forecast}}{MSE_{ref}}}}"></span>
</p><p>Business forecasters and practitioners sometimes use different termi=
nology. They refer to the PMAD as the MAPE, although they compute this as a=
 volume weighted MAPE. For more information, see <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Calculating_demand_forecast_accuracy" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Calculating demand forecast accuracy">Calculating demand forecast =
accuracy</a>.
</p><p>When comparing the accuracy of different forecasting methods on a sp=
ecific data set, the measures of aggregate error are compared with each oth=
er and the method that yields the lowest error is preferred.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Training_and_test_sets">Tra=
ining and test sets</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DForecasting&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Training and test sets"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>When evaluating the quality of forecasts, it is invalid to look at how w=
ell a model fits the historical data; the accuracy of forecasts can only be=
 determined by considering how well a model performs on new data that were =
not used when fitting the model. When choosing models, it is common to use =
a portion of the available data for fitting, and use the rest of the data f=
or testing the model, as was done in the above examples.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-e2.5_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fo=
recasting#cite_note-e2.5-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cross-validation">Cross-val=
idation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFore=
casting&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit section: Cross-va=
lidation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross-validation_(statistics)" =
title=3D"Cross-validation (statistics)">Cross-validation</a> is a more soph=
isticated version of training a test set.
</p><p>For <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross-sectional_data" t=
itle=3D"Cross-sectional data">cross-sectional data</a>, one approach to cro=
ss-validation works as follows:
</p>
<ol><li>Select observation <i>i</i> for the test set, and use the remaining=
 observations in the training set. Compute the error on the test observatio=
n.</li>
<li>Repeat the above step for  <i>i</i> =3D 1,2,..., <i>N</i> where <i>N</i=
> is the total number of observations.</li>
<li>Compute the forecast accuracy measures based on the errors obtained.</l=
i></ol>
<p>This makes efficient use of the available data, as only one observation =
is omitted at each step
</p><p>For time series data, the training set can only include observations=
 prior to the test set. Therefore, no future observations can be used in co=
nstructing the forecast. Suppose <i>k</i> observations are needed to produc=
e a reliable forecast; then the process works as follows:
</p>
<ol><li>Starting with <i>i</i>=3D1, select the observation <i>k + i</i>  fo=
r the test set, and use the observations at times  1, 2, ..., <i>k+i</i>=E2=
=80=931 to estimate the forecasting model. Compute the error on the forecas=
t for <i>k+i</i>.</li>
<li>Repeat the above step for <i>i</i> =3D 2,...,<i>T=E2=80=93k</i>  where =
<i>T</i> is the total number of observations.</li>
<li>Compute the forecast accuracy over all errors.</li></ol>
<p>This procedure is sometimes known as a "rolling forecasting origin" beca=
use the "origin" (<i>k+i -1)</i> at which the forecast is based rolls forwa=
rd in time.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-e2.5_28-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-e2.5-28"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Furt=
her, two-step-ahead or in general <i>p</i>-step-ahead forecasts can be comp=
uted by first forecasting the value immediately after the training set, the=
n using this value with the training set values to forecast two periods ahe=
ad, etc.
</p><p><i>See also</i>
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculating_demand_forecas=
t_accuracy" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Calculating demand forecast accu=
racy">Calculating demand forecast accuracy</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consensus_forecasts" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Consensus forecasts">Consensus forecasts</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecast_error" title=3D"Forec=
ast error">Forecast error</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Predictability" title=3D"Predi=
ctability">Predictability</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prediction_interval" title=3D"=
Prediction interval">Prediction intervals</a>, similar to <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval" title=3D"Confidence interval">=
confidence intervals</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reference_class_forecasting" t=
itle=3D"Reference class forecasting">Reference class forecasting</a></li></=
ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Seasonality_and_cyclic_beha=
viour">Seasonality and cyclic behaviour</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DForecasting&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D24"=
 title=3D"Edit section: Seasonality and cyclic behaviour"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Seasonality">Seasonality</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DForecasting&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: Seasonality"><span=
>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div=
>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seasonality" title=
=3D"Seasonality">Seasonality</a></div>
<p>Seasonality is a characteristic of a time series in which the data exper=
iences regular and predictable changes which recur every calendar year. Any=
 predictable change or pattern in a time series that recurs or repeats over=
 a one-year period can be said to be seasonal. It is common in many situati=
ons =E2=80=93 such as grocery store<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-29"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> or even in a Medical Examiner's office<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_no=
te-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>=E2=80=94that the demand depends on the day of the week. =
In such situations, the forecasting procedure calculates the seasonal index=
 of the "season" =E2=80=93 seven seasons, one for each day =E2=80=93 which =
is the ratio of the average demand of that season (which is calculated by M=
oving Average or Exponential Smoothing using  historical data corresponding=
 only to that season) to the  average demand across all seasons. An index h=
igher than 1 indicates that demand is higher than average; an index less th=
an 1 indicates that the demand is less than the average.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cyclic_behaviour">Cyclic be=
haviour</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFore=
casting&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit section: Cyclic b=
ehaviour"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<p>The cyclic behaviour of data takes place when there are regular fluctuat=
ions in the data which usually last for an interval of at least two years, =
and when the length of the current cycle cannot be predetermined. Cyclic be=
havior is not to be confused with seasonal behavior. Seasonal fluctuations =
follow a consistent pattern each year so the period is always known. As an =
example, during the Christmas period, inventories of stores tend to increas=
e in order to prepare for Christmas shoppers. As an example of cyclic behav=
iour, the population of a particular natural ecosystem will exhibit cyclic =
behaviour when the population decreases as its natural food source decrease=
s, and once the population is low, the food source will recover and the pop=
ulation will start to increase again. Cyclic data cannot be accounted for u=
sing ordinary seasonal adjustment since it is not of fixed period.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Limitations">Limitations</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DForecasting&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit section: Limitations"><span=
>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div=
>
<p>Limitations pose barriers beyond which forecasting methods cannot reliab=
ly predict. There are many events and values that cannot be forecast reliab=
ly. Events such as the roll of a die or the results of the lottery cannot b=
e forecast because they are random events and there is no significant relat=
ionship in the data. When the factors that lead to what is being forecast a=
re not known or well understood such as in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Stock_market" title=3D"Stock market">stock</a> and <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foreign_exchange_market" title=3D"Foreign exchang=
e market">foreign exchange markets</a> forecasts are often inaccurate or wr=
ong as there is not enough data about everything that affects these markets=
 for the forecasts to be reliable, in addition the outcomes of the forecast=
s of these markets change the behavior of those involved in the market furt=
her reducing forecast accuracy.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-https://www.otexts.org/f=
pp/1/1_4-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fo=
recasting#cite_note-https://www.otexts.org/fpp/1/1-4"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The concept of "self-destructing predictions" concerns the way in wh=
ich some predictions can undermine themselves by influencing social behavio=
r.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_31-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#cite_note-:0-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This is because "=
predictors are part of the social context about which they are trying to ma=
ke a prediction and may influence that context in the process".<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-:0_31-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Forecasting#cite_note-:0-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, a forecast that a =
large percentage of a population will become HIV infected based on existing=
 trends may cause more people to avoid risky behavior and thus reduce the H=
IV infection rate, invalidating the forecast (which might have remained cor=
rect if it had not been publicly known). Or, a prediction that cybersecurit=
y will become a major issue may cause organizations to implement more secur=
ity cybersecurity measures, thus limiting the issue.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Performance_limits_of_fluid=
_dynamics_equations">Performance limits of fluid dynamics equations</h3><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span>=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DForecasting&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit section: Performance limits of f=
luid dynamics equations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>As proposed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Lorenz" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Edward Lorenz">Edward Lorenz</a> in 1963, lon=
g range weather forecasts, those made at a range of two weeks or more, are =
impossible to definitively predict the state of the atmosphere, owing to th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chaos_theory" title=3D"Chaos the=
ory">chaotic nature</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flu=
id_dynamics" title=3D"Fluid dynamics">fluid dynamics</a> equations involved=
. Extremely small errors in the initial input, such as temperatures and win=
ds, within numerical models double every five days.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting#ci=
te_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
